According to Table 3, the CO2 emissions from energy consumption were lowest in the Northwest region, followed by the Southwest and Northeast. During phase III (2013–2017), the CO2 emissions followed a decreasing trend in the Southwest and Northeast regions, and high CO2 emissions from energy consumption were observed in the North, East, and Mid-South. The CO2 emissions increased rapidly in phase II (2003–2012), but the growth trend slowed in phase III (2013–2017), which is because the economic development in the North, East, and Mid-South regions is relatively rapid, while that of the Northwest, Southwest, and Northeast regions is relatively slow. Urbanization and industrialization will be promoted in economically developed regions, resulting in an increase in energy consumption and CO2 emissions (Zhang and Lin 2012).Table 3
